The truth is that Bezos had been antsy about the paper=E2=80=99s ideologica=
l leanings for
years. According to sources familiar with his thinking, he=E2=80=99s long w=
anted to bring the paper closer in line with his own free market, libertari=
an worldview. In the Fred Ryan era, this was sometimes transmitted as =E2=
=80=9Cliberal on social issues, conservative on economic issues,=E2=80=9D w=
hich probably failed to convey the nuances of his perspective. Anyway, both=
 Shipley and Post C.E.O. Will Lewis had actually been supportive of Bezos b=
ecoming more engaged on
the editorial side, as that is the one area where publishers have historica=
lly been able to wield influence without infringing on the sacrosanct prero=
gatives of the newsroom.

At the same time, both Shipley and Lewis strongly disagreed with Bezos=E2=
=80=99s desire to pull the endorsement, arguing that such a dramatic move s=
o close to the election would look bad and alienate the paper=E2=80=99s cor=
e audience. Rather than acquiesce to Bezos=E2=80=99s recommendation in late=
 September, Lewis, and especially Shipley,
spent the next month trying to change his mind, all while keeping the edito=
rial board in the dark about the fact that their endorsement of Kamala Harr=
is might get spiked.

=E2=80=9CFree Markets, Free People=E2=80=9D
-------------------------------

When the decision was announced, Shipley told his dispirited charges that, =
while he
consented to the =E2=80=9Cprinciple that you do not have to do presidential=
 endorsements,=E2=80=9D he disagreed with Bezos=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ctiming, =
and the way in which the timing could be read.=E2=80=9D But from Bezos=E2=
=80=99s standpoint, the bad timing had as much to do with Shipley=E2=80=99s=
 protracted deliberations over what, in his mind, had been a pretty clear d=
irective. Of course, Shipley had never shown the strong philosophical convi=
ctions of his predecessor, Fred Hiatt. He seemed to have stronger views abo=
ut the editing
and editorial process than any specific political or policy issue.

Last month, when Bezos was ready to implement his version of The Wall Stree=
t Journal=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfree markets, free people=E2=80=9D mandate, Sh=
ipley=E2=80=99s equivocation once again asserted itself, and again seemed t=
o irk Bezos. In his statement announcing the mandate and Shipley=E2=80=99s =
resignation, Bezos noted that he=E2=80=99d suggested to his Opinion editor =
=E2=80=9Cthat if the answer wasn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=98hell yes,=E2=80=99 then=
 it had to be =E2=80=98no.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D On first glance, the
anecdote appeared to telegraph Bezos=E2=80=99s own enthusiasm for the new e=
ditorial posture, but in retrospect, it was also a subtle acknowledgement o=
f his impatience with Shipley=E2=80=99s deliberations dating back at least =
as far as the non-endorsement.

Now, Bezos and Lewis have to identify a new Opinion leader who displays ent=
husiasm for the mandate that is commensurate with Bezos=E2=80=99s own. Alas=
, so far, all signs suggest that they have not yet identified who that lead=
er will be=E2=80=94or that they=E2=80=99re at least
playing it close to the chest.

