line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">When the decision was announced, Shipley told his dispirited char=
ges that, while he
consented to the =E2=80=9Cprinciple that you do not have to do presidential=
 endorsements,=E2=80=9D he disagreed with Bezos=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ctiming, =
and the way in which the timing could be read.=E2=80=9D But from Bezos=E2=
=80=99s standpoint, the bad timing had as much to do with Shipley=E2=80=99s=
 protracted deliberations over what, in his mind, had been a pretty clear d=
irective. Of course, Shipley had never shown the strong philosophical convi=
ctions of his predecessor, <strong>Fred Hiatt</strong>. He seemed to have s=
tronger views about the editing
and editorial process than any specific political or policy issue.<br/><br/=
>Last month, when Bezos was ready to implement his version of <em>The Wall =
Street Journal</em>=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfree markets, free people=E2=80=9D m=
andate, Shipley=E2=80=99s equivocation once again asserted itself, and agai=
n seemed to irk Bezos. In his statement announcing the mandate and Shipley=
=E2=80=99s resignation, Bezos noted that he=E2=80=99d suggested to his Opin=
ion editor =E2=80=9Cthat if the answer wasn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=98hell yes,=E2=
=80=99 then it had to be =E2=80=98no.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D On first glance, th=
e
anecdote appeared to telegraph Bezos=E2=80=99s own enthusiasm for the new e=
ditorial posture, but in retrospect, it was also a subtle acknowledgement o=
f his impatience with Shipley=E2=80=99s deliberations dating back at least =
as far as the non-endorsement.<br/><br/>Now, Bezos and Lewis have to identi=
fy a new Opinion leader who displays enthusiasm for the mandate that is com=
mensurate with Bezos=E2=80=99s own. Alas, so far, all signs suggest that th=
ey have not yet identified who that leader will be=E2=80=94or that they=E2=
=80=99re at least
playing it close to the chest.</p></div>
